<br>
First, I removed the kicks/bashes to only look at hits. I believe that doing so reduces the confusion/variance.<br>
<br>
Test# - AC - Avg hit - #hits<br>
  1 - 1985 - 227 - 484<br>
  2 - 1903 - 227 - 515<br>
  3 - 1899 - 230 - 521<br>
  4 - 1805 - 247 - 419<br>
  5 - 1706 - 241 - 645<br>
  6 - 1609 - 238 - 512<br>
  7 - 1502 - 252 - 477<br>
  8 - 2017 - 231 - 450<br>
  9 - 1985 - 222 - 418<br>
10 - 2101 - 219 - 245<br>
<br>
In order to determine if *all* these 4500ish hits could be from the same distribution (which would mean that AC was irrelevant) I determined the number of those that are for each of the 20 possible outcomes (the empirical distribution). This is very easily done using YALP.<br>
<br>
I then made samples of 500 hits each from that distribution (using a small homemade computer program) and took the average of each sample. I did that 1,000,000 times. Thus I had 1mill averages all from the same distribution - which I will now compare to the observed means.<br>
<br>
The min avg I got was 208 and the max average was 260 - so the observed values from 219 to 252 fall within that. But, thats obviously no very telling. Look instead at the following:<br>
<br>
&lt;= 219: 0.9%<br>
&lt;= 220: 1.4%<br>
&lt;= 221: 2.2%<br>
&lt;= 222: 3.3%<br>
<br>
&gt;= 247: 0.9%<br>
&gt;= 250: 0.2%<br>
&gt;= 252: 0.06%<br>
<br>
Thus, we can conclude that even at the 1% level of confidence the 2 outliers (219 and 252) do not stem from the same distribution.<br>
<br>
In short - the test Brutall made is large enough to statistically show that AC does have an effect - but only barely so if we want an alpha level of 1%.<br>
<br>
